caption:
We welcomed a new member to the family last month - baby Alice! @sannimccandless has posted more about it and has more updates, but the concise version is that it’s been a wild ride so far.
But Alice is thriving (she gained a double chin her first week) so all is well.
#ArcticAscent with me and @hazel_findlay is now streaming on @DisneyPlus and @hulu! Watch our epic climbing expedition across Greenland’s toughest peak.

@james_lucas took some pictures of a typical sport climbing day from this month - I’ve been settled into home life for the season working on sport climbing projects and training indoors. Pretty lovely way to spend the winter. So far I haven’t seen any real progress climbing-wise, but I’m enjoying myself and trying my hardest so that’s good enough for now. 
Pics are from a 13a warm up, my aspirational 14d project (which I’m mostly sucking on), and goofy belaying.

The official trailer for my @natgeotv show about Greenland just came out! No one has been to Ingmikortilaq in nearly two decades. Until now. Get ready for #ArcticAscent, a limited series premiering Sunday, February 4, at 8/7c on @natgeotv. Stream on @DisneyPlus and @hulu.

Happy New Year!! I’ve been meaning to post something for the New Year - this seems like the most important thing. @sannimccandless and I will be welcoming a new daughter into the family next month, which I’m sure will dominate our attention for 2024…
Our first daughter has been steadily growing up and becoming more of her own person. Right as it starts to feel more manageable and, dare I say, easier, we’re starting over from the beginning. But we’re all excited to add a little sister to the mix.
Photos from @jessglassberg while on a ladies sport climbing day with Sanni.

As we approach the end of year, I wanted to share a quick update on all things @honnoldfoundation. I know I say this every year, but, really, it’s pretty incredible to see how HF’s work has evolved over time. I got a chance to read through a report that highlighted some of our Partners’ impacts in the last few years, and it got me fired up. Just one example – in the last three years, our projects have built solar infrastructure in 245 communities with the potential to impact over 180,000 people. 

Meanwhile, the solar infrastructure we’ve helped install is enough to cover 9 acres worth of rooftops, which is honestly quite a bit.

But maybe the most eye popping stat was this: In the last three years, we’ve received far more projects than we could fund. If we had funded every single project submitted to us, we’d have brought solar to nearly 1.8 million people.

I’m proud of the work we’ve done, and I also know that there’s plenty more to do.

To everyone who supports our work at the Honnold Foundation, thank you! It’s really making a significant impact for people around the world.   And, if you’re considering and able to make an end of year donation towards climate action and social justice, I’d really appreciate you thinking of us at the Honnold Foundation. My own giving supports our team’s overhead, so every dollar that you give goes directly towards the communities we support – and all of those impacts I just mentioned.

Whether you can afford a little or a lot - all I ask is that you approach it a bit like a climbing project: make a gift that challenges you – something not too easy, but don’t go bankrupt or anything, either. Just make a gift that you can be proud of.

Anyways, hope you and your family have a nice holiday season!

Pic credits go to @peterrwalle, @natunguatemala, and @hasercambio.

This season’s final episode of Planet Visionaries is live! I had a nice chat with Rodrigo Medellín, the “batman of Mexico”. We recorded it on Halloween, our first themed episode - bats on Halloween (tho it was a coincidence…). Click the link in my bio to listen now. #RolexPartnershipContent @rolex #PerpetualPlanet

Fun afternoon scramble with @joshkmccoy and @stroh.light - we charged up Jubilant Song (7 pitch 5.8?) on Windy Peak at the end of the day. I forgot how big of a hike it is up to the route, but otherwise it all went pretty smoothly. Always fun to climb classics with your friends…

Last pic is the truck in its natural environment…

My @whoop Year in Review! Pretty classic that I turned into a cyclist this year. (Which is actually because the Whoop does a good job of automatically detecting cardio activities like biking to Alaska but I’m too lazy to add the climbing activities. They wind up reflected in the data, I just don’t parse them into discrete activities.) I definitely climbed and hiked more than anything else this year…

Here’s a @_drew_smith_ photo of me on the @kilterboard, my whoop Year in Review data and a goofy portrait from a gym photo shoot this fall.

In Part 2 of Adapted, Mo Beck and Jim Ewing head to the Lotus Flower Tower. Hugh Herr embarks on life after climbing and tackles one of humanity’s greatest challenges. Denny Kowska seeks to build an adaptive community from the ground up. Hear @hugh.herr, @mo.in.mountains, @jimewing, @mushymuscles and @alexhonnold at the Spotify link in our bio or wherever you find your podcasts.

Happy family portrait!! Baby June is steadily becoming big girl June! @sannimccandless

Climbing’s first phenom survives a near death experience and life altering accident on Mount Washington. In rural Maine, a young girl born without a hand discovers climbing. In the aftermath of an accident, an engineer resolves to complete a lifelong dream. Hugh Herr (@hugh.herr), Mo Beck (@mo.in.mountains) and Jim Ewing (@jim.ewing) take us on a journey in a two part series about human potential, generational friendships and the power of climbing.
